<TITLE> Shanghai property tycoon Zhou on trial again </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Oct 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Disgraced Shanghai property tycoon Zhou Zhengyi appeared in court on Wednesday on new charges, just over a year after serving a three-year term for stock market fraud and falsifying documents. Zhou, once China's 11th richest man with an estimated worth of $320 million, was charged at the Shanghai Municipal People's Court with misappropriation of funds, bribery and forging VAT receipts. "The trial would last for days because of the complicated nature of the charges," the official Xinhua news agency said, citing court sources. Zhou, 45, a former snack-shop owner who rose to become president of Shanghai-based property firm Nongkai Development (Group) Co, was detained last October as part of a 3.7 billion yuan social security fund scandal that brought down the city's former Communist Party secretary, Chen Liangyu. There has been no official link drawn between Chen and Zhou, Xinhua noted. In August, four former prison officials were given up to 11 years in jail for taking bribes in return for easing Zhou's previous stint as a guest of the Shanghai prison syst
